data.label: Citrix Online
data.description: The Citrix Online protocol was the umbrella term used for protocols used by the GoToX product suite: GoToMeeting, GoToMyPC, GotToAssist, and more.  The protocols are now obsolete.

data.label: Meebo
data.description: Meebo was an instant messaging and social networking service provider in the late 2000s.  The software was acquired by Google and merged with Google+.

data.label: Quake
data.description: The Quake Protocol was used in earlier generations of the industry-changing Quake first person shooter video game.

data.label: Skype Inbound
data.description: This version of the Skype Inbound DPI detection has been merged with the Skype detection.

data.label: EPP Domain Provisioning
data.description: The Extensible Provisioning Protocol (EPP) is a protocol used by domain registries to help manage, provision, and transfer domain names.  The protocol is no longer tracked.

data.label: iMesh
data.description: iMesh was a media and file sharing service that was discontinued in 2016.

data.label: Filetopia
data.description: Filetopia was a free peer-to-peer file sharing client that included chat and instant message features.  The service has been discontinued.

data.label: Telegram Call
data.description: The Telegram Call Protocol is a voice and video call solution integrated into the Telegram app.

data.label: Ethereum
data.description: The Ethereum protocol is a cryptocurrency implementation for the creation, transfer, and verification on the Ethereum network.

data.label: Protocol Buffers
data.description: Protocol Buffers (protobuf) is an open protocol developed by Google for serializing structured data, similar to XML or JSON.

data.label: CAN
data.description: The Controller Area Network (CAN) protocol is used in automotive and industrial applications. It is designed for real-time communication between microcontrollers and devices.

data.label: RMCP
data.description: The Remote Management Control Protocol (RMCP) is a protocol used in hardware management, usually in the field of Intelligent Platform Management Interface (IPMI) solutions.

data.label: HAProxy
data.description: The HAProxy (High Availability Proxy) Protocol is used to coordinate load balancing and proxying for TCP and HTTP-based applications.

data.label: Meta Call
data.description: The Meta Call Protocol is a voice and video call solution integrated into several Meta products, notably Facebook and Instagram.

data.label: HTTP/2
data.description: HTTP/2 is a modern version of the HTTP protocol. It improves web browsing performance with multiplexing, header compression and more.

data.label: SLP
data.description: The Service Location Protocol (SLP) is a networking protocol that allows network devices and services to discover and advertise the availability of services within a local area network (LAN).

data.label: Thrift
data.description: The Apache Thrift protocol is part of a cross-language framework for building scalable and high-performance services with data serialization and remote procedure calls (RPCs).

data.label: Bitcoin
data.description: The Bitcoin protocol is a cryptocurrency implementation for the creation, transfer, and verification on the Bitcoin network.

data.label: XMPPS
data.full_name: Secure Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol
data.description: The Secure Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPPS) is a set of open technologies for instant messaging, presence, multi-party chat, voice, video and collaboration.

data.label: SRTP
data.description: The Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP) is used to deliver audio and video over networks. It is used by telephony, video conferencing, and general streaming media devices.

data.label: OICQ
data.description: OICQ (Open ICQ) is a protocol used in the Tencent QQ instant messaging solution.  The software is popular in China and other parts of Asia.

data.label: Source Engine
data.description: The Source Engine protocol was developed by Valve Corporation and used in various video games: Half-Life 2, Portal, Counter-Strike, and more.

data.label: BACnet
data.description: BACnet, which stands for Building Automation and Control Networks, is a communication protocol specifically developed for building automation and control systems.

data.label: Heroes of the Storm
data.description: The Heroes of the Storm protocol provides game server services.  The game is developed by Blizzard Entertainment.

data.label: Meraki Cloud
data.description: The Cisco Meraki Protocol provides a tunneling service for Meraki devices to connect to Cisco cloud infrastructure.

data.label: Tailscale
data.description: Tailscale is a simple, fast and modern VPN based on WireGuard.  It aims to be simple to use with little configuration required.

data.label: TP-Link SHP
data.description: The TP-Link Smart Home Protocol is used to connect Kasa Smart devices with a companion app.

data.label: TivoConnect
data.description: The TivoConnect protocol provides automatic machine discovery for two or more Tivo media player systems running on the same network.

data.label: Syncthing
data.description: The Syncthing protocol is used to synchronizes files between two or more computers in real time.

data.label: Munin
data.description: The Munin protocol is part of an open-source software tool that monitors IT infrastructure such as networks, servers, virtual machines, and cloud services.

data.label: LINE Call
data.description: The LINE Call protocol is call/videconferencing system used in the popular LINE messaging mobile app.

data.label: Kismet
data.description: The Kismet remote capture protocol is used to send wireless monitoring (sniff) data to a central server.

data.label: FastCGI
data.description: FastCGI is a protocol for interfacing interactive programs with a web server.  It is a variant of the CGI protocol.

data.label: CryNetwork
data.description: CryNetwork is a gaming protocol used on the CryEngine platform.  The protocol is used for connecting gaming clients, synchronizing events, matchmaking, and more.

data.label: Avast
data.description: The Avast protocol provides push notification services for Avast antivirus solutions.

data.label: Elasticsearch
data.description: The Elasticsearch binary protocol is used for communications between nodes in a cluster: master elections, node orchestration, shard management, and more.

data.label: Tuya LAN
data.description: The Tuya LAN protocol is used for intercommunication by many IoT devices including LED lights, lightbulbs, smart plugs, and more.

data.label: NAT-PMP
data.description: NAT Port Mapping Protocol (NAT-PMP) is used to establish network address translation (NAT) settings and port forwarding configurations automatically.

data.label: Syslog/TLS
data.description: Syslog/TLS is a standard message logging protocol found in Unix/Linux systems. The secure syslog protocol allows for logging from one system to be sent to a remote logging server.

data.label: AliCloud Server
data.description: The AliCloud Server protocol is a custom communications channel for accessing and managing servers.

data.label: Threema
data.description: The Threema protocol is used by the identically named application - a paid and proprietary end-to-end encrypted instant messaging service.

data.label: PIM
data.description: PIM (Protocol Independent Multicast) is a multicast routing protocol, that is used to send traffic from a single source to multiple destinations across a network.

data.label: PGM
data.description: Pragmatic General Multicast (PGM) is a multicast computer network transport protocol that provides a reliable sequence of packets to multiple recipients simultaneously.

data.label: Xiaomi Messaging
data.description: Xiaomi is a Chinese designer and manufacturer of consumer electronics.  The company uses a proprietary messaging protocol in their products.

data.label: Ultrasurf
data.description: The Ultrasurf protocol provides a proxy/VPN solution designed to bypass Internet censorship firewalls.

data.label: Toca Boca
data.description: The Toca Boca protocol is by the identically named video game studio.  The studio is focused on child-friendly applications for tablets and smartphones.

data.label: SD-RTN
data.description: The Software Defined Real-time Network (SD-RTN) protocol is proprietary protocol from Agora.  It is a variant of a content delivery network, but designed for streaming and low-latency.

data.label: RSH
data.description: The Remote Shell Protocol is used for remotely running a command on a remote computer. It has since been superceded by Secure Shell (SSH).

data.label: Riot Games
data.description: The Riot Games protocol is used for game server management and connections.

data.label: RakNet
data.description: RakNet is networking middleware developed by Oculus VR, Inc. for use in the video game industry.

data.label: DASH
data.description: Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP (DASH) is an adaptive bitrate streaming technique that enables high quality streaming of media content over the Internet delivered from conventional HTTP web servers.

data.label: i3D
data.description: The i3D protocol is a low-latency solution primarily used by game servers.  The protocol was developed by Ubisoft's i3D.net - a global high-performance hosting provider.

data.label: Zabbix
data.description: The Zabbix protocol is part of an open-source software tool that monitors IT infrastructure such as networks, servers, virtual machines, and cloud services.

data.label: Z39.50
data.description: Z39.50 is an international standard client–server, application layer communications protocol for searching and retrieving information from a database over a TCP/IP computer network, developed and maintained by the Library of Congresss.

data.label: WebSocket
data.description: WebSocket is an advanced technology that makes it possible to open a two-way interactive communication session between a browser and a server.

data.label: VXLAN
data.description: Virtual Extensible LAN (VXLAN) is a network virtualization technology that attempts to address the scalability problems associated with large cloud computing deployments.

data.label: Targus GetData
data.description: Targus GetData is a proprietary protocol used for bandwidth testing.  The protocol was developed by TARGUSinfo (acquired by Neustar in 2011).

data.label: SOAP
data.description: Simple Object Access Protocol (SOAP) is a messaging protocol used to exchange information between different machines and computer networks.

data.label: S7comm
data.description: The S7 Communication protocol is a used to exchange data between programmable logic controllers (PLCs) typically used in manufacturing.  The protocol was developed by Siemens.

data.label: NATS
data.description: The NATS protocol is a text-based publish/subscribe messaging protocol. It can be used for building distributed systems, device communications and more.

data.label: MongoDB
data.description: The MongoDB Wire Protocol is a simple socket-based, request-response style protocol used to communicate between clients and servers.

data.label: Secure IRC
data.description: Secure Internet Relay Chat (Secure IRC) is a text-based chat system for instant messaging designed for group communication in discussion forums.  This is a sister protocol to the unencrypted IRC protocol.

data.label: IEC 104
data.description: The IEC 60870-5-104 (IEC 104) protocol is a standard for power system monitoring, telecontrol, teleprotection, and associated telecommunications for electric power systems.

data.label: HSRP
data.description: The Hot Standby Router Protocol (HSRP) is a Cisco proprietary protocol used to provide redundancy across multiple routers in a network.

data.label: HP VM Group Management
data.description: The HP Virtual Machine Group Management protocol is part of the virtualization suite used in HP server environments.

data.label: GTP-U
data.description: The GPRS Tunnelling Protocol (GTP) is a group of IP-based communications protocols used within GSM, UMTS, LTE and 5G NR radio networks.  GTP-U is used to carry user data inside mobile networks.

data.label: GTP-Prime
data.description: The GPRS Tunnelling Protocol (GTP) is a group of IP-based communications protocols used within GSM, UMTS, LTE and 5G NR radio networks.  GTP' (Prime) is used to transfer charging data inside mobile core networks.

data.label: GTP-C
data.description: The GPRS Tunnelling Protocol (GTP) is a group of IP-based communications protocols used within GSM, UMTS, LTE and 5G NR radio networks.  GTP-C is used on the control plane inside mobile core networks.

data.label: Genshin Impact
data.description: Genshin Impact is an action role-playing game developed and published by miHoYo. It was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 4/5, iOS, and Android.

data.label: EtherNet/IP
data.description: Ethernet/IP (Industrial Protocol) is one of the leading industrial protocols in the United States and is widely used in a range of industries including factory, hybrid and process.

data.label: DNSCrypt
data.description: DNSCrypt is a protocol that encrypts, authenticates and optionally anonymizes communications between a DNS client and a DNS resolver. It is designed to prevent DNS spoofing.

data.label: DNP3
data.description: The Distributed Network Protocol 3 (DNP3) is a set of communications protocols used between devices in process automation systems.  It is primarily used by utilities (water, electric, etc.).

data.label: Check Point HA
data.description: The Check Point High Available (HA) protocol provides support for clustering Check Point hardware firewall devices.

data.label: Cassandra
data.description: The Cassandra protocol is a database cluster protocol.  It was developed for Apache Cassandra - an open-source distributed NoSQL database management system designed to handle large amounts of data.

data.label: CAPWAP
data.full_name: Control and Provisioning of Wireless Access Points
data.description: The Control And Provisioning of Wireless Access Points (CAPWAP) protocol is a standard that enables a central wireless access controllers to manage wireless access points.

data.label: Avast Real Site
data.description: Avast Real Site (was Secure DNS) is a protocol that protects against DNS hijacking.  The protocol is part of antivirus products from Avast.

data.label: Among Us
data.description: Among Us is an online multiplayer social deduction game developed and published by game studio Innersloth. The game was inspired by the party game Mafia.

data.label: DoQ
data.description: DNS over QUIC (DoQ) is a protocol for performing remote Domain Name System (DNS) resolution via the QUIC protocol.

data.label: DoT
data.description: DNS over TLS (DoT) is a protocol for performing remote Domain Name System (DNS) resolution via the (Transport Layer Security) TLS protocol.

data.label: NNTPS
data.description: The secure Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) is an application protocol used for transporting Usenet news articles and binaries between servers and user client applications.

data.label: MQTTS
data.description: MQTTS is an encrypted machine-to-machine (M2M)/"Internet of Things" connectivity protocol. It was designed as an extremely lightweight publish/subscribe messaging transport.

data.label: SIPS
data.description: The secure Session Initiation Protocol (SIPS) is a VoIP signaling protocol used for initiating, maintaining, and terminating real-time sessions that include voice, video and messaging applications.

data.label: FTPS Data
data.description: Secure FTP is a protocol used to transfer files between computers. The control portion of the secure file transfer typically happens on TCP port 990, while the data transfer often happens on port 989.

data.label: Snapchat
data.description: The Snapchat protocol sits on top of QUIC.  It is used to reduce latency and optimize text, video and audio streams.

data.label: Zoom
data.description: The Zoom protocol is used by the Zoom videoconferencing application.  The protocol is used to create separate channels for video, audio and other media routing.

data.label: Skype/Teams
data.description: The Skype/Teams protocol is used by Microsoft's consumer Skype application, as well as the business-oriented Teams platform.

data.label: WhatsApp Call
data.description: WhatsApp is a popular messaging and voice over IP (VoIP) service owned by Facebook. The WhatsApp Call protocol detects calls and VoIP.

data.label: Google Meet/Duo
data.description: Google Meet/Duo is a communication platform developed by Google which includes instant messaging, video chat, SMS and VOIP features. Google Meet is a successor to Google Hangout

data.label: DTLS
data.description: Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications that prevents eavesdropping, tampering, and message forgery.

data.label: DoH
data.description: DNS over HTTPS (DoH) is a protocol for performing remote Domain Name System (DNS) resolution via the HTTPS protocol.

data.label: Apple Push
data.description: The Apple Push Notification Service is a product from Apple that enables third party developers to send notifications to Apple devices.

data.label: Diameter
data.description: The Diameter protocol is an authentication, authorization and accounting protocol for computer networks.  It is a successor to the RADIUS protocol.

data.label: LISP
data.description: Locator/ID Separation Protocol (LISP) is a protocol that allows global Internet routing tables to scale by aggregating address blocks.

data.label: CSGO
data.description: The CSGO protocol is used by the popular game series Counter Strike Global Offensive.

data.label: FIX
data.description: The Financial Information eXchange (FIX) protocol is an electronic communications protocol used and securities transactions and markets.

data.label: SOME/IP
data.description: SOME/IP is an automotive middleware solution used in cameras, heads up units, telematics and other automotive functions.

data.label: DRDA
data.description: Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) is a protocol used to encapsulate database commands and responses.  Though an open standard, DRDA is only used in IBM DB2 environments.

data.label: Git
data.description: Git is a source code control system used in software development.

data.label: Rx
data.description: Rx is a client-server RPC protocol, an extended and combined version of the older R and RFTP protocols

data.label: MQTT
data.description: MQTT is a machine-to-machine (M2M)/"Internet of Things" connectivity protocol. It was designed as an extremely lightweight publish/subscribe messaging transport. It is useful for connections with remote locations where a small code footprint is required.

data.label: EEP
data.description: The Extensible Encapsulation Protocol (EEP) provides a way to duplicate IP traffic and is used by SIP/Voice-over-IP solutions. The protocol was formerly nicknamed HEP.  The solution is not in wide use.

data.label: Teredo IPv6
data.description: Teredo is a transition technology that gives full IPv6 connectivity for IPv6-capable hosts that are on the IPv4 Internet but have no native connection to an IPv6 network.

data.label: StarCraft
data.description: The StarCraft protocol is used in an online video game of the same name.  It is a real-time strategy game developed and published by Blizzard Entertainment.

data.label: Tinc
data.description: The Tinc protocol is used for compressed and encrypted virtual private networks (VPNs).  The open source implementation is available on a number of different platforms including Linux, xBSD, MAC OS X, Microsoft Winodos, iOS, Android and more.

data.label: SMPP
data.description: The Short Message Peer-to-Peer Protocol (SMPP) is used in the telecommunications industry for delivering messages on mobiles.

data.label: WireGuard
data.best_practices: WireGuard does not use a standard port for communication, so it can be more difficult to block on some firewalls/gateways.
data.description: WireGuard is a simple, fast and modern VPN that utilizes state-of-the-art cryptography. It aims to be faster, simpler, leaner, and more useful than IPsec and OpenVPN.

data.label: Canon BJNP
data.description: BJNP is a custom LAN service discovery protocol used by Canon printers and scanners.  Computer systems use this protocol to auto-discover Canon devices on the network.

data.label: Google Hangout
data.description: Google Hangouts is a communication platform developed by Google which includes instant messaging, video chat, SMS and VOIP features.  The solution merged with Google Meet/Duo.

data.label: MPEG Transport Stream
data.description: The MPEG Transport Stream protocol is typically used to multicast video or web camera streams across multiple LAN clients.

data.label: HTTPS
data.description: The HTTPS protocol is the secure web protocol used by web sites and modern web-driven technologies.  HTTP is the unsecure version of this protocol.

data.label: KakaoTalk Voice
data.description: KakaoTalk - also known as KaTalk - is a free mobile instant messaging application for smartphones with free text and call features.

data.label: AMQP
data.description: The Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP) is a low-level message queuing protocol used to connect systems across different operating systems and platforms.  The protocol is implemented in RabbitMQ, Apache Qpid, and other message brokers.

data.label: Ookla Speedtest
data.description: The Ookla Speedtest is a very popular tool for measing bandwidth from an ISP.  Part of the testing phase uses a custom Ookla protocol.

data.label: EAQ
data.full_name: Entitade Aferidora da Qualidade de Banda Larga
data.description: EAQ is an eccentric protocol that is rarely seen in the wild.

data.label: WhatsApp STUN
data.description: WhatsApp is a popular messaging and voice over IP (VoIP) service owned by Facebook.  The WhatsApp STUN protcol detects messages and notifications.

data.label: QUIC
data.best_practices: If you are a Chrome web browser user, you can view QUIC connection information by typing in the following web address: chrome://net-internals/#quic.
data.description: QUIC is a UDP protocol used by Google Chrome and Chromium web browsers.  The protocol is designed for low-latency and performance.

data.label: Telegram
data.description: Telegram is a cross-platform cloud-based instant messaging, video calling, and VoIP service that uses end-to-end encryption.

data.label: VHUA
data.description: VHUA is a deprecated protocol that was used for Skype-like services in China.

data.label: Pando Media Booster
data.description: Pando Media Booster is a now defunct protocol used for sharing files - notably large video and media files - via a peer-to-peer network.

data.label: Redis
data.description: Redis is an in-memory database store used in backend infrastructure.  The protocol is used to connect clients to Redis datastores.

data.label: H.248 MGCP
data.description: Media Gateway Control Protocol (MGCP), also known as H.248 and Megaco, is a standard protocol for handling the signaling and session management needed during a multimedia conference.

data.label: ZeroMQ
data.description: ZeroMQ is an asynchronous messaging library that can run without a dedicated message broker.

data.label: FTP Data
data.best_practices: FTP is an old school protocol that has been around since the early 1970s. Unlike the encrypted FTPS protocol, the basic FTP protocol uses clear text passwords so user authentication should be avoided in this mode.
data.description: FTP is a protocol used to transfer files between computers. The data portion of the file transfer often passes through TCP port 21, while the control typically happens on TCP port 20.

data.label: Real Time Messaging
data.description: The Real Time Messaging Protocol - RTMP - is a widely used streaming video protocol used in Flash Players and other video clients.  Though RTMP is being replaced by newer standards, it is still a widely used today.

data.label: Nintendo
data.description: Nintendo is a video game hardware and software vendor that produces the Wii, DS, Switch and many other products.  Some of the services use a custom Nintendo protocol.

data.label: SOCKS5
data.description: SOCKS is a protocol that exchanges network packets between a client and server through a proxy server.  The protocol can proxy both TCP and UDP traffic.

data.label: Collectd
data.description: The collectd protocol is used to transfer and store performance data of computers and network equipment.

data.label: Whois
data.description: Whois is a query and response protocol that is widely used for querying domain names, IP addresses, ASNs, and other network information.

data.label: Corba
data.description: The CORBA protocol is designed to facilitate the communication of systems that are deployed on diverse operating systems, programming languages and hardware platforms.

data.label: Oracle
data.description: Oracle Database is a popular relational database server.  Similar products include MySQL, Microsoft SQL Server, and Postgres.

data.label: Rsync
data.description: The rsync protocol is used to efficiently transfer and synchronize files between computers.

data.label: RTP Control Protocol
data.description: The Real-Time Transport Control Protocol (RTCP) is a protocol that works with Real-Time Protocol (RTP) to monitor data delivery on large multicast networks.

data.label: Skinny
data.description: The Skinny Client Control Protocol (SCCP) is a proprietary network terminal control protocol for session signaling with VoIP gateways and phones.

data.label: TeamSpeak
data.best_practices: TeamSpeak is popular with gamers, so if you see such traffic on your network then there is a good chance that gaming is happening as well.
data.description: TeamSpeak is a voice-over-IP (VoIP) system that allows users to voice chat online.  Though very popular in the gaming world, TeamSpeak is also used in education, training and business.

data.label: Cisco VPN
data.best_practices: VPNs can not only be used to connect remote locations, but also be used to bypass your firewall/DNS policies. Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: The Cisco VPN protocol is a proprietary IPsec variant developed by Cisco.

data.label: New Office Environment
data.description: The New Office Environment protocol is voice-over-IP (VoIP) protocol used by Alcatel-Lucent compatible telephone systems.

data.label: OpenVPN
data.best_practices: VPNs can not only be used to connect remote locations, but also be used to bypass your firewall/DNS policies. Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: OpenVPN is a virtual private network (VPN) protocol.  The main implementation is developed under an open source license and is widely deployed.  VPN clients are available for Windows, Mac, Linux, Android and iOS.

data.label: H.323
data.description: H.323 is, much like SIP (Session Initiation Protocol), a protocol designed for the setup, management, and termination of a media session.

data.label: Spotify Synchronization
data.description: Most Spotify traffic occurs over the standard HTTP or HTTPS protocol, but the Spotify Synchronization protocol is still used for sharing music across the network.

data.label: RemoteScan
data.description: RemoteScan is a protocol used to share printers, scanners and imaging devices on a local area network (LAN).

data.label: Link-Local Multicast
data.description: The Link-Local Multicast Name Resolution (LLMNR) is a protocol based on the Domain Name System (DNS) packet format that allows both IPv4 and IPv6 hosts to perform name resolution for hosts on the same local link.

data.label: WS-Discovery
data.description: Web Services Dynamic Discovery (WS-Discovery or WSD) is a UDP-based communications protocol for auto-discovery used by printers, cameras and other types of devices on a local network.  The Universal Plug-and-Play (uPnP) protocol is similar.

data.label: GPRS Tunneling
data.description: The GPRS (General Packet Radio Service) Tunneling Protocol is used for GSM, UMTS, LTE and other mobile networks.

data.label: SAP
data.description: Session Announcement Protocol (SAP) is used for multicast data session broadcasts and communications.  For example, it can be used to present a list of available audio streams to a user.

data.label: Lotus Notes
data.description: Lotus Notes is a brand of groupware that is now owned by IBM. Lotus Notes is used with a variety of local and collaborative server applications, including email, calendars, and personal information managers.

data.label: TeamViewer
data.description: The TeamViewer Protocol is a protocol that allows remote access and remote control to information systems, allowing maintenance of computers and other devices.

data.label: RADIUS
data.full_name: Remote Authentication Dial In User Service
data.description: RADIUS (Remote Authentication Dial-In User Service) provides centralized authentication, authentication and accounting management.  The protocol is widely deployed in Internet Service Providers and large enterprises, as well as often used for wireless netw

data.label: Viber
data.description: The Viber protocol is used to provide end-to-end encryption for voice calls and instant messaging conversations.

data.label: WhatsApp Chat
data.description: WhatsApp is a popular messaging and voice over IP (VoIP) service owned by Facebook.  The WhatsApp Chat protocol is a variant of XMPP and handles messaging and notifications.

data.label: Apache JServ
data.description: The Apache JServ Protocol (AJP) is a protocol used to proxy inbound web request through to an application server.  The protocol is in use by the Tomcat platform.

data.label: Check_MK
data.description: The Check_MK protocol is used by the similarly named Check_MK IT monitoring system.  The protocol is used to monitor server and container systems in IT infrastructure.

data.label: Citrix Thin Client
data.description: Independent Computing Architecture (ICA) is a proprietary protocol for an application server system, designed by Citrix Systems. The protocol lays down a specification for passing data between server and clients.

data.label: HTTP Web Proxy
data.best_practices: Proxies can be used to not only optimize network experience, but also bypass your firewall/DNS policies. Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: The HTTP Web Proxy protocol is used to tunnel HTTP connections from a local client via a remote server.

data.label: HTTP Web Proxy Connect
data.best_practices: Proxies can be used to not only optimize network experience, but also bypass your firewall/DNS policies. Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: The HTTP Web Proxy Connect protocol is used to tunnel HTTPS connections from a local client via a remote server.

data.label: sFlow
data.description: The sFlow protocol is a technology for monitoring traffic in data networks.  It is typically incorporated in switches and routers.

data.label: NetFlow
data.description: The Netflow protocol is a technology developed by Cisco for monitoring traffic in data networks.  It is typically incorporated in switches and routers.

data.label: DCE/RPC
data.full_name: Distributed Computing Environment / Remote Procedure Calls
data.description: DCE/RPC is a specification for a remote procedure call mechanism that defines both an over-the-network protocol and APIs.

data.label: Skype for Business
data.description: The Skype for Business protocol was a custom solution derived from the Lync software solution.  The product reached end-of-life in July 2021 and users were expected to migrate to Microsoft Teams.

data.label: Dropbox
data.best_practices: Most Dropbox traffic is still transferred over standard SSL connections, but you should still see the Dropbox LAN Sync protocol in use when the Dropbox app is active on a target system.
data.description: Dropbox is a file hosting and storage service that is used to synchronize files across multiple computing devices.  The Dropbox protocol - also called LAN Sync - allows computers on a local network to synchronize files across other computers.

data.label: World of Kung Fu
data.description: The World of Kung Fu protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game of the same name.

data.label: Warcraft III
data.description: The Warcraft III protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game World of Warcraft.

data.label: PPTP
data.best_practices: The PPTP protocol has well known security issues, so use an alternative VPN solution.  In addition, VPN can not only be used to connect remote locations, but also be used to bypass your firewall/DNS policies.  Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: The PPTP protocol is an obsolete virtual private network (VPN) protocol.  It was developed in 1999 by a consortium led by Microsoft and was a popular VPN solution in the 2000s.

data.label: Microsoft SQL Server
data.description: The MS SQL protocol is used by the Microsoft SQL Server platfrom - a relational database management system developed by Microsoft.

data.label: MapleStory
data.description: The MapleStory protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game of the same name.

data.label: LDAP/AD
data.full_name: Lightweight Directory Access Protocol / Active Directory
data.description: LDAP is a directory service protocol that manages users, groups, passwords, systems and other assets.  Popular implementations of LDAP directory services include OpenLDAP, Microsoft Active Directory, and Novell eDirectory.

data.label: Kerberos
data.description: Kerberos is a computer network authentication protocol, which allows people communicating over a non-secure network to prove their identity to one another in a secure manner.

data.label: ActiveSync
data.description: ActiveSync was a mobile data synchronization app developed by Microsoft.  It synchronized data with handheld devices and desktop computers.  The solution has been replaced by native Microsoft Windows support.

data.label: Guild Wars
data.description: The Guild Wars protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game of the same name.

data.label: Florensia
data.description: The Florensia protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game Florensia.

data.label: Fiesta
data.description: The Fiesta protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game Fiesta Online.

data.label: Dofus
data.description: The Dofus protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game of the same name.

data.label: Crossfire
data.description: CrossFire is an online tactical first-person shooter game developed by Smilegate Entertainment for Microsoft Windows.

data.label: Armagetron
data.description: The Armagetron gaming protocol was developed for the game of the same name - a multiplayer snake game in 3D based on the light cycle sequence from the film Tron.

data.label: DHCP IPv6
data.best_practices: IPv6 hosts may automatically generate IP addresses internally using stateless address autoconfiguration (SLAAC), or they may be assigned configuration data with DHCPv6.
data.description: The Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol version 6 (DHCPv6) is a network protocol for configuring IPv6 hosts with IP addresses.

data.label: ICMP - Ping IPv6
data.description: The Internet Control Message Protocol version 6 (ICMPv6) is a protocol that provides diagnostic, troubleshooting, control and error message services.

data.label: Truphone
data.description: The Truphone protocol is a communication framework used by Truphone, a global mobile network operator, to enable seamless voice, messaging, and data services.

data.label: SIP
data.description: The Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) is a VoIP signaling protocol used for initiating, maintaining, and terminating real-time sessions that include voice, video and messaging applications.

data.label: Aimini
data.description: Aimini was a peer-to-peer Windows desktop solution that allowed users to share files, search, chat, and exchange information.  The desktop software is no longer available.

data.label: Stealthnet
data.description: The Stealthnet protocol is a secure, decentralized peer-to-peer communication protocol used for anonymous file sharing and messaging.

data.label: Apple File Services
data.description: The Apple Filing Protocol (AFP) is part of Apple File Service (AFS).  It offers filer services for macOS and classic Mac OS.

data.label: TFTP
data.description: Trivial File Transfer Protocol (TFTP) is a simple protocol used for transferring files.  It is typically used on a local network to bootstrap VoIP systems and other network-centric devices.

data.label: Asterisk IAX
data.description: Inter-Asterisk eXchange (IAX) is a communications protocol native to the Asterisk private branch exchange (PBX) software, and is supported by a few other softswitches, PBX systems, and softphones.

data.label: MGCP
data.description: The Media Gateway Control Protocol (MGCP) is a signaling and call control communications protocol used in voice over IP (VoIP) telecommunication systems.

data.label: NNTP
data.best_practices: Usenet was originally used for online forums, but is now typically used for file sharing.
data.description: The Network News Transfer Protocol (NNTP) is an application protocol used for transporting Usenet news articles and binaries between servers and user client applications.

data.label: SSH Secure Shell
data.description: Secure Shell is a network protocol that provides a secure channel over the Internet.  It is commonly used for command line operations to remote computer systems, but it is also used for basic VPN and tunneling.

data.label: TLS/SSL
data.best_practices: The Netify engine is able to deconstruct the hostnames used in SSL connections which in turn makes it possible to detect specific applications on your network.  Use Netify's Application Filter to delve into SSL protocol details.
data.description: The TLS/SSL protocol is used to encrypt network traffic across a wide variety of protocols including HTTP, FTP, SMTP and more.

data.label: pcAnywhere
data.description: pcAnywhere is a discontinued suite of computer programs by Symantec which allowed a user to connect to a remote personal computer.

data.label: VNC
data.description: The Virtual Network Computing (VNC) protocol is a remote desktop sharing system to control another computer in a different location.

data.label: Remote Desktop Protocol
data.best_practices: RDP can be used to bypass your firewall/DNS policies.  It is also a very common attack vector for cyberthreats.  Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) provides a way for systems to access a desktop or application hosted on a remote host.

data.label: RTP
data.description: The Real-time Transport Protocol is used to deliver audio and video over networks.  It is used by telephony, video conferencing, and general streaming media devices.

data.label: IP in IP
data.best_practices: VPNs can not only be used to connect remote locations, but also be used to bypass your firewall/DNS policies. Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: IP in IP is a low-level tunneling protocol used to connect two IP networks.  Though the the payloads are not encrypted, the protocol is used to connect networks.

data.label: OSPF
data.description: Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) is a routing protocol that is used to find the best path between the source and the destination router.  It is used amongst routers to optimize traffic flow.

data.label: SCTP
data.description: Stream Transmission Control Protocol (SCTP) is a connection-oriented protocol provides message-oriented data transfer.  The protocol is deployed in telecom networks.

data.label: EGP
data.description: The Exterior Gateway Protocol (EGP) was a routing protocol used to connect different autonomous systems on the Internet from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s, when it was replaced by Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).

data.label: IGMP
data.description: IGMP is a communication protocol used by hosts and adjacent routers for multicasting communication with IP networks.  It is typically used by IPTV and other multicast applications.

data.label: ICMP - Ping
data.description: The Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) is a protocol that provides diagnostic, troubleshooting, control and error message services.

data.label: GRE
data.best_practices: VPNs can not only be used to connect remote locations, but also be used to bypass your firewall/DNS policies. Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: GRE (General Routing Encapsulation) is a low-level tunneling protocol used by various VPN implementations: Cisco, IPsec, PPTP and more.  The protocol can be used to transport IPv4, IPv6, multicast and other low-level protocols.

data.label: IPsec
data.best_practices: VPNs can not only be used to connect remote locations, but also be used to bypass your firewall/DNS policies. Investigate any unauthorized use on your network.
data.description: The IPsec (Internet Protocol Security) is a secure protocol suite that authenticates and encrypts network traffic for VPN services.  It is a very widely used VPN protocol.

data.label: STUN
data.description: STUN is a standardized protocol for traversing network firewall/gateways for applications of real-time voice, video, messaging, and other interactive communications.

data.label: Telnet
data.best_practices: You should not see the Telnet protocol on your network and any activity should be investigated.  The secure SSH protocol is a good alternative to Telnet.
data.description: Telnet is a text-oriented protocol typically used to connect to remote devices via a command line interface.  The protocol is one of the oldest protocols still in use -- it was developed in 1969.

data.label: World of Warcraft
data.description: The World of Warcraft protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game of the same name.

data.label: Half-Life 2
data.description: The Half-Life 2 protocol is the communication and data exchange framework used in the online multiplayer role-playing game of the same name.

data.label: Steam
data.description: The Steam protocol is a customized file transfer protocol used by the game company of the same name.

data.label: VRRP
data.description: Virtual Router Redundancy Protocol (VRRP) is an open standard fault-tolerant protocol that provides redundancy and improves network reliability.

data.label: BattleField
data.description: The Battlefield gaming protocol was used in the game of the same name - a first-person shooter video game.  The protocol has been deprecated.

data.label: AOL Instant Messenger
data.full_name: Open System for Communication in Realtime
data.description: AIM (AOL Instant Messenger) was an instant messaging and presence application created by America Online (AOL). The software used the OSCAR instant messaging protocol to communicate in real time.  The software is now obsolete.

data.label: XMPP
data.description: The Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP) is a set of open technologies for instant messaging, presence, multi-party chat, voice, video and collaboration.  The protocol was originally named Jabber.

data.label: Anything In Anything
data.description: Anything In Anything (AYIYA) is a computer networking protocol for managing IP tunneling protocols in use between separated Internet Protocol networks. It is most often used to provide IPv6 transit over an IPv4 network link.

data.label: IRC
data.description: The Internet Relay Chat (IRC) protocol provides a way to create text-based chat clients.

data.label: Certificateless SSL
data.description: The Certificateless SSL engine was used to detect SSL traffiic without certificate information.  The modern protocol engine is now always able to extract SSL details, so this protocol is now obsolete.

data.label: Soulseek
data.description: Soulseek is a peer-to-peer file sharing application primarily used to exchange music. The solution is now a niche product with social networking features.

data.label: Thunder
data.description: The Thunder protocol was used in a peer-to-peer download manager from the Xunlei company.  Today, Xunlei uses BitTorrent, HTTP, FTP and other protocols for their download manager product.

data.label: QQLive
data.description: QQlive is a popular peer-to-peer streaming media technology for the Chinese market.  The service is available via the web and on mobile devices.

data.label: HTTP Download
data.description: The HTTP download protocol provided detection for large files downloaded via the web/HTTP protocol.  This protocol detector is now obsolete.

data.label: TVUPlayer
data.description: TVUPlayer was a software application used for watching TV over the Internet.  The service was shutdown in February 2013.

data.label: TvAnts
data.description: TVants was a peer-to-peer TV software application that provided music, movies, news and more. The software was primarily targeted for the Chinese market and is now obsolete.

data.label: SopCast
data.description: SopCast is a simple, free way to broadcast video and audio or watch the video and listen to radio on the Internet using peer-to-peer technology.

data.label: SHOUTcast
data.description: SHOUTcast is a cross-platform proprietary software application for streaming media over the Internet. The software is typically used for creating Internet radio stations.

data.label: Zattoo
data.description: Zattoo is a TV streaming service that offers live TV and on-demand content for computers, mobiles, tablets and other network devices.

data.label: PPStream
data.description: PPStream (PPS Net TV) is a Chinese peer-to-peer streaming video network.  Programs vary from Chinese movies to Japanese anime, sports channels, as well as popular American TV and films.

data.label: PPLive
data.description: The PPLive protocol was a peer-to-peer video streaming protocol primarily used in China.  The peer-to-peer protocol is now obsolete, and PPLive has been replaced by PPTV.

data.label: Icecast
data.description: Icecast is an open-source streaming media server typically used to create Internet radio stations and other private media servers.

data.label: Secure IMAP Mail
data.description: The Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) protocol is used by e-mail clients to synchronize mail from a remote server.  Microsoft Outlook, Apple Mail, Gmail for Android, iPhone Mail and many other mail clients use IMAPS for synchronizing mail.

data.label: Real Time Streaming Protocol
data.description: The Real Time Streaming Protocol (RTSP) is a streaming video protocol designed to provide play, record, pause and other standard video controls.  The protocol is usually used with the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) and Real-time Control Protocol (RTCP)

data.label: QQ Instant Messenger
data.description: Tencent QQ is a very popular instant messenger used in Asia.  QQ has approximately 1 billion active accounts worldwide.

data.label: Xbox
data.description: The Xbox protocol is used by Microsoft's Xbox gaming system.  The protocol is used by games like Call of Duty, Grand Theft Auto, and many others.

data.label: WhatsApp Video
data.description: WhatsApp is a popular messaging and voice over IP (VoIP) service owned by Facebook.  The WhatsApp Video protocol detects calls and video calls.

data.label: Modbus
data.description: Modbus is a serial communications protocol that has become the de facto standard for connecting industrial electronic devices.  The protocol was originally published by Modicon (now Schneider Electric).

data.label: Nest Protect
data.description: The Google Nest Protect log update protocol is used by Nest smoke / carbon dioxide detectors.  It is a proprietary binary protocol for logging status updates to Nest Cloud servers.

data.label: Mining
data.description: The Mining Protocol covers a variety of cryptocurrency mining engines: Bitcoin, Ethereum, ZCash, Monero, and more.

data.label: Windows SMB v2/v3
data.description: The Server Message Block (SMB) protocol provides file and print services to systems on the network. This detection is for version 2 and 3 of the protocol.

data.label: Memcached
data.description: The Memcached Protocol is used by the popular Memcache memory caching system.  The caching system is used to speed up data lookups and used by web sites, applications and other software engines.

data.label: Signal Call
data.description: The Signal Call protocol is a method for traversing firewalls for real-time voice and video.  A separate protocol (Signal Protocol) is used for secure messaging.

data.label: Skype
data.description: The Skype protocol is used by the once popular Skype video and voice communications application.  Skype is available on computers, tablets, mobile devices, and smartwatches.  The software can also be used to connect to the telephone network.

data.label: BitTorrent
data.best_practices: If not managed properly, BitTorrent software can consume an awful lot of bandwidth.
data.description: BitTorrent is the most popular peer-to-peer file sharing protocol. It is typically used to download large files, as well as movies, music and other media.

data.label: eDonkey
data.description: eDonkey was a popular peer-to-peer file sharing protocol used by several different software clients including eMule, Morpheus and Shareza.

data.label: Gnutella
data.description: Gnutella was a popular peer-to-peer file sharing protocol used by dozens of software clients including Limewire, BearShare, and Morpheus.  The protocol is still in use today.

data.label: FastTrack
data.description: The FastTrack protocol was used by several different peer-to-peer file sharing applications: Kazaa, Grokster, iMesh and others.

data.label: OpenFT
data.description: The Open FastTrack (OpenFT) protocol is a peer-to-peer file sharing protocol.

data.label: Kontiki
data.description: The Kontiki peer-to-peer protocol drives the Kontiki Delivery Management System - a video and content delivery platform.

data.label: Ubiquiti AirControl 2
data.description: Ubiquiti AirControl is a web-based network management application used to managed Ubiquity devices - routers, switches, WiFi access points and more.

data.label: Facebook Zero
data.description: Facebook Zero was an initiative undertaken by Facebook in collaboration with Internet providers, whereby the providers waive data (bandwidth) charges for accessing Facebook on phones using a text-only version.  The solution has been retired.

data.label: Secure SMTP Mail
data.best_practices: Keep an eye on the size and number of SMTPS connections going through your network.  If you see a spike in traffic, it could be spam or virus traffic from a malware infected system on your network.
data.description: The Secure Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTPS) is used for sending e-mail messages.

data.label: VMware
data.description: The VMware protocol is used to connect clients - for example vSphere - to VMware server systems.

data.label: CoAP
data.description: The Constrained Application Protocol (CoAP) is a specialized protocol for machine-to-machine applications such as smart energy and building automation.

data.label: Direct Connect
data.description: DirectConnect is a defunct peer-to-peer protocol that was popular in the early Napster era - 2000 to 2005.  This protocol is for the history books.

data.label: AppleJuice
data.description: Applejuice is a defunct file sharing protocol that had some popularity in Germany.  This protocol is for the history books.

data.label: Secure POP Mail
data.description: The Secure Post Office Protocol (POP3S) is an encrypted protocol used by e-mail clients to retrieve mail from a remote server. The secure IMAP mail protocol is much more prevalent these days, but the POP3S protocol is still in use.

data.label: Direct Download Link
data.description: Direct download link (DDL) is a term used in the file sharing community to describe direct downloads from popular file hosting sites.  Though peer-to-peer file sharing is more popular, direct download sites are still popular for some types of content.

data.label: FTPS Control
data.description: Secure FTP is a protocol used to transfer files between computers. The control portion of the secure file transfer typically happens on TCP port 990, while the data transfer often happens on port 989.

data.label: MySQL
data.description: MySQL is a popular relational database server.  Similar products include Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle Database and Postgres.

data.label: Postgres
data.description: PostgreSQL, or simply Postgres, is a popular open source relational database server.  Similar products include MySQL, Microsoft SQL Server, and Oracle Database.

data.label: DHCP
data.description: The Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) is a way for servers to automatically provide IP addresses to devices on a local network.

data.label: System Logger
data.description: Syslog is a standard message logging protocol found in Unix/Linux systems.  The syslog protocol allows for logging from one system to be sent to a remote logging server.

data.label: Windows SMB v1
data.best_practices: The SMBv1 protocol was developed in the 1980s and has past its prime.  The protocol is insecure and a security incident waiting to happen.  If you see this protocol on your network, please take action.
data.description: The Server Message Block (SMB) protocol provides file and print services to systems on the network.  Though primarily used by Microsoft Windows systems, macOS, Linux and other operating systems also support the protocol.

data.label: X-Windows Display
data.description: The X Display Manager Control Protocol (XDMCP) is used by the X Windows system commonly found in Unix/Linux systems.

data.label: SNMP
data.description: Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) is a protocol used for collecting technical information on network-connected devices: bandwidth, CPU usage, memory usage, system load, and much more.

data.label: BGP
data.description: The Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) is used to manage routing across the Internet.  Notably, the protocol allows routers to quickly adapt to Internet backbone connection changes.

data.label: SSDP
data.best_practices: The multicast 239.255.255.250 IPv4 and ff0X::c IPv6 addresses are used to announce services on a local network.  You may see these two IP addresses in your Netify reports.
data.description: The Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) protocol is used by the Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) protocol.  The protocol provides broadcast and discovery of network services on a local network.

data.label: NFS
data.description: The Network File System (NFS) protocol is used for creating file sharing services for primarily UNIX/Linux systems. Typically, the protocol is deployed to provide central storage over a local network.

data.label: Windows Networking
data.description: NetBIOS over TCP/IP is a naming service and session handler used by Windows networks.  The protocol allows for computers on a small local network to communicate with each other.

data.label: Network Time Protocol
data.description: NTP is a network protocol used to synchronize clocks over the Internet.  It is one of the most widely used protocols - servers, mobile phones, tablets, embedded devices, and plain old computer systems all use it.

data.label: Multicast DNS
data.description: The Multicast Domain Name System (mDNS) provides a way for systems to resolve hostnames on a small network even when a local DNS server does not exist.  Some types of media services and printers use mDNS for auto-discovery on a local network.

data.label: HTTP
data.description: The HTTP protocol is the unencrypted web protocol used by web sites and other web-based technologies.  HTTPS is the secure/encrypted version of this protocol.

data.label: Internet Printing
data.description: The Internet Printing Protocol (IPP) provides a communication channel between computing systems and printers.  The protocol is typically used by print server systems and supports authentication, encryption and access control.

data.label: DNS
data.description: The Domain Name System (DNS) translates human-readable computer names - for example, www.netify.ai - into numerical IP addresses required for networking.

data.label: IMAP Mail
data.best_practices: IMAP can be both encrypted (via STARTTLS) and unencrypted, so there is a risk that usernames and passwords are sent across the network in an insecure manner.  You might want to consider using the alternative IMAPS protocol to guarantee encryption.
data.description: The Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP) protocol is used by e-mail clients to synchronize mail from a remote server.  The more secure IMAPS protocol is more widely deployed, but IMAP is still in use.

data.label: SMTP Mail
data.best_practices: Keep an eye on the size and number of SMTP connections going through your network.  If you see a spike in traffic, it could be spam or virus traffic from a malware infected system on your network.
data.description: The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) is used for sending e-mail messages.

data.label: POP Mail
data.best_practices: POP can be both encrypted (via STARTTLS) and unencrypted, so there is a risk that usernames and passwords are sent across the network in an insecure manner.  You might want to consider using the alternative POP3S protocol to guarantee encryption.
data.description: The Post Office Protocol (POP) is a protocol used by e-mail clients to retrieve mail from a remote server.  The IMAP mail protocol is much more prevalent these days, but the protocol is still in use.

data.label: FTP Control
data.best_practices: FTP is an old school protocol that has been around since the early 1970s.  Unlike the encrypted FTPS protocol, the basic FTP protocol uses clear text passwords so user authentication should be avoided in this mode.
data.description: FTP is a protocol used to transfer files between computers. The control portion of the file transfer typically happens on TCP port 21, while the data transfer happens on TCP port 20 or potentially other ports.

data.label: Unclassified
data.description: The deep packet inspection engine is able to dive into network traffic and extract even complex protocols like encrypted BitTorrent.  However, some traffic is ... mysterious.
